ork; his concept of the bond between humanity and nature; and his novel philosophies of perception, embodiment, and "wild" Being. Eco-phenomenologies of living places such as Central Park in New York City, Midwestern farmlands, and communal household dwellings of Pacific Northwest Coast people are closely examined. The contributors also explore Merleau-Ponty's philosophy for environmental ethics and develop notions such as vital values, somatic empathy, and interspecies sociality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aAbram, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBigwood, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Edward S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCataldi, Suzanne L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Duane H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Martin C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunphy-Blomfield, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamrick, William S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarney, Maurita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Molly Hadley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJung, Hwa Yol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirkman, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiberman, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLocke, Patricia M., econtr